[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":677},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F10\u002Flearn-hexo-27-github-actions-deploy\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F10\u002Flearn-hexo-27-github-actions-deploy\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F10\u002Flearn-hexo-27-github-actions-deploy\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F10\u002Flearn-hexo-27-github-actions-deploy\u002F":654,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F10\u002F10\u002Flearn-hexo-27-github-actions-deploy\u002F":663},"\u002Fhexo\u002F20201010\u002F1989721020\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":638,"date":639,"description":19,"extension":640,"lang":641,"meta":642,"navigation":204,"path":643,"readingMinutes":644,"seo":645,"standalone":646,"stem":647,"tags":648,"tldr":651,"updated":639,"url":652,"__hash__":653},"content\u002Fen\u002FHexo\u002Flearn-hexo-27-github-actions-deploy.md","(27) Learning Hexo from Scratch - Tricks: Auto-Deploy with GitHub Actions","2012798910",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":629},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,31,34,42,52,58,61,65,77,93,96,99,103,109,115,119,129,132,138,142,157,162,178,488,491,497,501,507,565,568,614,617,625],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Next up is another CI: GitHub Actions.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"github-actions","GitHub Actions",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":29,"src":30},"I want private repos to auto-deploy too","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-09-16%2015.50.43.png",[17,32,33],{},"Some folks want auto-deploy for private repos too — maybe their articles aren't ready to publish yet, still being written, but they still want to keep auto-deploy in place. Personally I don't actually use auto-deploy because I edit my articles a lot — I'll write a little, commit for version control, write some more, commit again. I'd probably burn through a CI quota pretty fast with that habit.",[17,35,36,37,41],{},"Back on topic. The previous post covered Travis CI, which is great for open source projects but requires the commercial version for private repos. Not exactly ideal for a small blogger. Luckily ",[38,39,40],"del",{},"Microsoft Daddy bought GitHub"," (wait, what?) GitHub itself offers a CI service called GitHub Actions, which fits our needs perfectly. A couple of things to know — GitHub Actions has limits:",[43,44,45,49],"ul",{},[46,47,48],"li",{},"Each account gets 2,000 minutes of execution time, which is about 33.33 hours",[46,50,51],{},"Upgrading to Pro doesn't give you unlimited — you get an extra 1,500 minutes",[17,53,54,55,57],{},"But as I said, ",[38,56,40],{}," (wait, what?) GitHub is generous — the quota resets roughly every 15 days. For a small blogger with builds that take a few seconds, that's plenty.",[17,59,60],{},"So let's jump in. I'll skip the private repo setup since it's the same as a public repo, just with the visibility set to private.",[12,62,64],{"id":63},"generate-an-ssh-deploy-key","Generate an SSH deploy key",[17,66,67,68,72,73,76],{},"Before using GitHub Actions, generate an SSH key. Run this in your terminal to generate a private key (",[69,70,71],"code",{},"actions-deploy-key",") and a public key (",[69,74,75],{},"actions-deploy-key.pub","):",[78,79,84],"pre",{"className":80,"code":81,"language":82,"meta":83,"style":83},"language-cmd shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","ssh-keygen -f actions-deploy-key\n","cmd","",[69,85,86],{"__ignoreMap":83},[87,88,91],"span",{"class":89,"line":90},"line",1,[87,92,81],{},[17,94,95],{},"(If it asks for a passphrase — \"Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase): \" — leave it blank, just hit Enter.)",[17,97,98],{},"The key files will be generated wherever your terminal currently is.",[12,100,102],{"id":101},"add-the-private-key-to-the-private-repo","Add the private key to the private repo",[17,104,105,106,108],{},"Add ",[69,107,71],{}," (the private key) to your private repo under Settings -> Secrets -> Add a new secret.",[17,110,111],{},[27,112],{"alt":113,"src":114},"Add a new secret","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F1600243787720.jpg",[12,116,118],{"id":117},"add-the-public-key-to-the-blog-repo","Add the public key to the blog repo",[17,120,121,122,124,125,128],{},"Then add ",[69,123,75],{}," (the public key) to your blog repo (",[69,126,127],{},"xxxx.github.io",") under Settings -> Deploy Keys -> Add deploy key.",[17,130,131],{},"Make sure to check \"Allow write access — Can this key be used to push to this repository? Deploy keys always have pull access.\" — otherwise it won't be able to push.",[17,133,134],{},[27,135],{"alt":136,"src":137},"Add deploy key","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F1600244128684.jpg",[12,139,141],{"id":140},"create-the-action","Create the Action",[17,143,144,145,148,149,152,153,156],{},"In your Hexo project, create a ",[69,146,147],{},".github"," folder, then a ",[69,150,151],{},"workflows"," folder inside it. So you'll end up with two nested folders. Finally, create a file called ",[69,154,155],{},"hexoAcions.yml",":",[17,158,159],{},[27,160],{"alt":155,"src":161},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-09-16%2017.37.59.png",[17,163,164,165,169,170,173,174,177],{},"Contents below. Once more, ",[166,167,168],"strong",{},"make sure"," to update ",[69,171,172],{},"git config --global user.name \"xxxx\""," and ",[69,175,176],{},"git config --global user.email \"xxxx@gmail.com\""," to your own GitHub name and email — otherwise it won't work:",[78,179,183],{"className":180,"code":181,"language":182,"meta":83,"style":83},"language-yml shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","name: 'hexo deploy'\n\n## Trigger when master branch gets a push\non:\n  push:\n    branches:\n    - master\njobs:\n  build:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n    - name: Checkout\n      uses: actions\u002Fcheckout@v1\n    - name: Use Node.js 12.x\n      uses: actions\u002Fsetup-node@v1\n      with:\n        node-version: \"12.x\"\n    - name: init)init ssh\n      run: |\n          mkdir -p ~\u002F.ssh\u002F\n          echo \"${{secrets.HEXO}}\" > ~\u002F.ssh\u002Fid_rsa\n          chmod 600 ~\u002F.ssh\u002Fid_rsa\n          ssh-keyscan github.com >> ~\u002F.ssh\u002Fknown_hosts\n          git config --global user.name \"xxxx\"\n          git config --global user.email \"xxxx@gmail.com\"\n    - name: A)npm install\n      run: |\n        npm install\n    - name: B)npm install -g hexo-cli\n      run: |\n        npm install -g hexo-cli\n    - name: C) hexo d -g\n      run: |\n        hexo d -g\n","yml",[69,184,185,199,206,213,223,231,239,248,256,264,275,283,295,306,318,328,336,347,359,371,377,383,389,395,401,407,419,428,434,446,455,461,473,482],{"__ignoreMap":83},[87,186,187,191,195],{"class":89,"line":90},[87,188,190],{"class":189},"sKpQp","name",[87,192,194],{"class":193},"sMAXC",": ",[87,196,198],{"class":197},"sTRMh","'hexo deploy'\n",[87,200,202],{"class":89,"line":201},2,[87,203,205],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":204},true,"\n",[87,207,209],{"class":89,"line":208},3,[87,210,212],{"class":211},"sQrFR","## Trigger when master branch gets a push\n",[87,214,216,220],{"class":89,"line":215},4,[87,217,219],{"class":218},"sCcAr","on",[87,221,222],{"class":193},":\n",[87,224,226,229],{"class":89,"line":225},5,[87,227,228],{"class":189},"  push",[87,230,222],{"class":193},[87,232,234,237],{"class":89,"line":233},6,[87,235,236],{"class":189},"    branches",[87,238,222],{"class":193},[87,240,242,245],{"class":89,"line":241},7,[87,243,244],{"class":193},"    - ",[87,246,247],{"class":197},"master\n",[87